router

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

I created the following directive:

```
@Directive({
   selector: '[sectionLink]',
   standalone: true,
   hostDirectives: [
      {
         directive: RouterLink
      }
   ]
})
export class SectionLinkDirective implements OnInit {

   private readonly _navigationService = inject(NavigationService);
   private readonly _routerLinkDirective = inject(RouterLink);

   @Input()
   public sectionLink: [section: SectionName, parameter: any | null] | SectionName;

   public ngOnInit(): void {
      const link = this._navigationService.resolveSectionLink(
         typeof this.sectionLink === 'string' ? this.sectionLink : this.sectionLink[0],
         typeof this.sectionLink === 'string' ? null : (this.sectionLink[1] ?? null)
      );

      this._routerLinkDirective.routerLink = link;
      this._routerLinkDirective.ngOnChanges({ routerLink: new SimpleChange(null, link, true) });
   }
}
```

This directive is used to apply a `routerLink` directive based on the `sectionLink` value that resolves to a route.
This works well, however, I'm forced to call the `ngOnChanges` hook in order to trigger the `updateHref` method of the `RouterLink` directive or the `href` of the link won't be defined and its CSS cursor won't change.

It would be nice to either make `updateHref` public in order to be able to call it or even better (I think), try and call this method in a setter for `routerLink` and other inputs triggering a change in the URL.

If this issue seems is accepted, I would be glad to try and make a pull request for it.

